  "computational_details": [],
  "unmapped_findings": [
    "Figure 1 shows the iron corner of the Fe-Mn-Al phase diagram with approximately 1% C at 1150°C, distinguishing single-phase gamma-solid solution alloys from two-phase gamma-plus-alpha alloys.",
    "Figure 2 provides micrographs of alloys with 25% Mn, 10% Al, 1% C (I) and 20% Mn, 10% Al, 1% C (II) after quenching from 1150°C and after quenching plus aging at 600°C for 50 h; pure text pipeline has no image pixels.",
    "Figure 3 shows mechanical properties of the alloy with 27.5% Mn, 9.1% Al, and 0.92% C in relation to aging temperature (16 h), presenting sigma_b, sigma_0.2, psi, and delta values at 450, 500, and 550°C.",
    "Table 1 lists mechanical properties for alloy G30Yu9 in the quenched condition (sigma_b = 84 kg/mm^2, sigma_0.2 = 57 kg/mm^2, delta = 72%, psi = 70%) but numerical values for the aged conditions and for the alloy with 26.1% Mn, 10.2% Al, 1.02% C are not visible in the provided table snippet.",
    "Table 2 reports magnetic permeability (G/Oe) of five specific alloy compositions after quenching and after quenching plus aging 20 h at 600°C; specific values range from 1.007 to 1.038 (quenched) and 1.040 to 3.860 (aged), with the highest aged permeability of 3.860 for 0.97% C, 30.5% Mn, 10.6% Al.",
    "The alloy with 25% Mn, 10% Al, 1% C exhibited a sharp hardness increase after aging at 600°C from HRB 86-88 to HRC 35-37.",
    "Alloys with about 10% Al obtain optimal mechanical properties by aging at 475-500°C, while aging at 550-575°C substantially reduces ductility and strength.",
    "Alloys with 12-14% Al have low plasticity and ductility both after quenching and after aging.",
    "The oxidation resistance after 500 h at 700°C in air showed a weight increase of 6-12.5 g/m^2 for alloys with over 8% Al, compared to 6.2 g/m^2 for steel 1Kh17N2 and 118 g/m^2 for boiler steel 20KhM.",
    "Density measurements show that with increasing aluminum from 6% to 10%, density decreases from 7.24 to 6.68 g/cm^3; alloys with 9% Al and 25-30% Mn have a density of 6.75-6.85 g/cm^3.",
    "Machinability of these Fe-Mn-Al alloys is similar to that of 18/8 steels, and they can be processed by hot and cold working.",
    "Over 100 heats were prepared in the composition range 5-45% Mn, 2-14% Al, and 0.05-1.5% C, melted in a laboratory induction furnace under helium or in a 30-kg commercial furnace."
